Project Title: A Data-Driven Review of Delphinid Skull Studies Using 3D Geometric Morphometrics

Problem Statement

This project addresses the research question of how Geometric Morphometrics (GM) has been used to understand the diversity of skull shapes in odontocetes (toothed whales), with a specific focus on the family Delphinidae. The systematic review seeks to synthesize existing literature to identify trends, biases, and key findings in the application of GM to this field.

Data Sources

The data for this systematic literature review was sourced from several well-respected academic search engines to ensure comprehensive coverage of scientific, peer-reviewed articles. The databases used were: Web of Science / ScienceDirect / Scopus / Ingenta Connect / Semantic Scholar

Methodology

A systematic literature review was conducted using a defined set of keywords: Geometric morphometric, skull shape, odontocete, and delphinid. The search was limited to articles published between 1990 and March 2021, a period that aligns with the introduction of the GM term. Only peer-reviewed studies that used 2D or 3D GM to investigate skull shape variations were included. Studies that used non-GM methods, focused on other marine mammal clades (e.g., mysticetes, pinnipeds), or examined structures other than skulls were excluded. The references from all identified publications were also reviewed to ensure no relevant studies were missed.

Key Findings

Growth in Research: Thirty-two relevant studies were identified. Although the overall number of GM studies on odontocete skulls has grown steadily since the first publications in 2002, it is still an early and developing field. Over half of the studies were published between 2015 and 2021, indicating a recent surge in research.

Taxonomic Focus: The review found that 5 families and 14 genera were investigated across the 32 studies. The families Delphinidae, Iniidae, Phocoenidae, and Pontoporidae were the most frequently studied. This is likely due to Delphinidae being the largest odontocete family and more commonly represented in museum collections.

Geographical Bias: While many studies included specimens from multiple regions, a clear geographical bias was observed. The North Atlantic, Mediterranean, and North Sea were the most represented regions. This is followed by the South Pacific, South Atlantic, and Indian Oceans.

Research Areas: The main research areas addressed in the studies were evolutionary ecology, ontogeny, sexual dimorphism, taxonomy and phylogeny, functional morphology, and population structure. A common approach was to compare skull structures between or within species, which falls under the scope of evolutionary ecology.

Tools & Technologies

This project used the following programming languages and software tools for data analysis and visualization:

RStudio for data visualization and figure generation using packages such as ggplot2, UpSetR, Venneuler, and the tidyverse.

Python for data cleaning and table creation prior to analysis in R, using pandas, matplotlib.pyplot, matplotlib.patches, numpy, and chorddiag.

Power BI for data cleaning and preliminary data exploration.

Tableau for interactive dashboard creation and visualization.

Venneuler Field Study

# Install The Packages

# Load The Libraries

library(ggvenn)
library(eulerr)
library(venneuler)

# Load Your File // This is a binary presence/absence table for 8 sets and 10 observations
Venn <- read.csv("../1_Data/Data_Cleaned/Venneuler_FieldStudy.csv")

## Create Euler object 

# Select your columns in the table
selected_columns <- Venn[, 1:8] 

# Fit stores all the information needed to draw the     Euler diagram
fit <- venneuler(selected_columns) 

# Prevents labels from being written
fit$labels <- NA 

## Colors and Labels
# Labels
my_labels <- c("Taxonomy & Phylogeny", 
               "Functional morphology", 
               "Interspecific variation", 
               "Evolutionary ecology", 
               "Ontogeny", 
               "Sex dimorphism", 
               "Intraspecific variation",
               "Population Structure")

# Colors
cols <- c("blue","red","green","purple","orange","cyan","brown","magenta")

## Plot Circles
plot(fit, col = cols, alpha = 0.3, border = NA)

# Extract centers and radii #
xs <- fit$centers[,1]
ys <- fit$centers[,2]
radii <- fit$diameters / 2

# Compute outward direction for labels #
plot_cx <- mean(range(xs))
plot_cy <- mean(range(ys))
dx <- xs - plot_cx
dy <- ys - plot_cy
dist <- sqrt(dx^2 + dy^2)
dist[dist == 0] <- 1
ux <- dx / dist
uy <- dy / dist

margin <- strheight("M") * 2.0
base_label_x <- xs + ux * (radii + margin)
base_label_y <- ys + uy * (radii + margin)

# Label adjustments
x_offset <- c(-0.1,0.1, -0.2, 0.05, 0, -0.1, 0, 0)
y_offset <- c(-0.1, 0, 0, -0.05, -0.1, 0, -0.025, 0)

# Draw leader lines and labels
for (i in 1:8) {
  factor <- 0.80
  x_end <- xs[i] + (base_label_x[i] + x_offset[i] - xs[i]) * factor
  y_end <- ys[i] + (base_label_y[i] + y_offset[i] - ys[i]) * factor
  segments(xs[i], ys[i], x_end, y_end, col = cols[i], lty = 3)
  
  # label 
  text(base_label_x[i] + x_offset[i], 
       base_label_y[i] + y_offset[i], 
       my_labels[i], 
       col = cols[i], 
       font = 3, 
       cex = 0.55)}

PYTHON CODING

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import os # We need this to handle operating system interactions like file paths

plt.rcParams['axes.titlesize'] = 45   # default title font size
plt.rcParams['axes.titleweight'] = 'bold'

outdir = '.' # Specifies that the files and graphics should be in the set directory

# The file should be in the same directory, or you need to provide the full path
df = pd.read_csv("MasterFile_Cleaned.csv")

# Split columns by slash
df["Species"] = df["Species"].str.split("/")
df["Oceans/Seas"] = df["Oceans/Seas"].str.split("/")

# Put names in different columns
df = df.explode("Species")
df["Species"] = df["Species"].str.strip()

df = df.explode("Oceans/Seas")
df["Oceans/Seas"] = df["Oceans/Seas"].str.strip()

# --- Create cross-tab table ---
species_ocean_table = pd.crosstab(df["Species"], df["Oceans/Seas"])
species_ocean_table.to_excel(os.path.join(outdir, "species_by_ocean.xlsx"))

# --- Generate donut charts per ocean ---

# --- Load the modified Excel file --- I have cleaned it based on biological knowledge

import matplotlib.patches as mpatches
import random

species_ocean_table = pd.read_excel("species_by_ocean_cleaned.xlsx", index_col=0)

plt.rcParams['axes.titlesize'] = 45   # default title font size
plt.rcParams['axes.titleweight'] = 'bold'

# Function to show counts instead of percentages
def make_autopct(values):
    def my_autopct(pct):
        total = sum(values)
        val = int(round(pct*total/100.0))
        return f"{val}"
    return my_autopct


# Get all unique species
all_species = species_ocean_table.index.tolist()


# Assign default matplotlib colors
default_colors = plt.rcParams['axes.prop_cycle'].by_key()['color']
species_colors = {species: (random.random(), random.random(), random.random()) for species in all_species}


# Create a single legend figure
legend_elements = [
    mpatches.Patch(color=color, label=species)
    for species, color in species_colors.items()
]

plt.figure(figsize=(6, 12))
plt.legend(
    handles=legend_elements,
    loc="center",
    title="Species",
    fontsize=10,
    title_fontsize=12,
    ncol=2)
    
plt.axis("off")  # hide empty plot
plt.tight_layout()

outdir = os.path.join(".", "donut")
os.makedirs(outdir, exist_ok=True)

plt.savefig(os.path.join(outdir, "species_legend.png"), dpi=150, transparent=True, bbox_inches="tight")
plt.close()


# 3. PLOTTING LOOP 
for ocean in species_ocean_table.columns:
    counts = species_ocean_table[ocean]
    counts = counts[counts > 0]
    
    if counts.empty:
        continue  # skip oceans with no counts
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))
    wedges, texts, autotexts = plt.pie(
        counts,
        labels=None,
        autopct=make_autopct(counts),
        startangle=90,
        wedgeprops=dict(width=0.4)
    )

    outdir = os.path.join(".", "donut")
    os.makedirs(outdir, exist_ok=True)

  # Style the count labels
    plt.setp(autotexts, size=25, weight="bold", color="Black")

    plt.title(f"{ocean}", fontsize=20, fontweight="bold")
    plt.tight_layout()

    # Save with transparent background
    plt.savefig(
        os.path.join(outdir, f"donut_{ocean.replace(' ', '_')}.png"),
        dpi=150,        transparent=True
    )
    plt.close()

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load Data
FieldStudy = pd.read_csv("Upset_FieldStudy.csv")

# Get column names
columns = FieldStudy.columns.tolist()

# Compute coocurrence Matrix
co_matrix = np.dot(FieldStudy.T, FieldStudy)
np.fill_diagonal(co_matrix, 0)  # remove self-links

co_df = pd.DataFrame(co_matrix, index=columns, columns=columns)

# Export Matrix in your directory
co_df.to_csv("/mnt/c/1.MorganeCanada/Project-1-/1_Data/Data_Raw/cooccurrence_table.csv")

 Chord Diagram with R Studio

# Install packages 
install.packages("devtools")
devtools::install_github("mattflor/chorddiag")
install.packages("htmlwidgets") # Used to save the interactive plot
install.packages("circlize") # Often useful for general circular plotting

# Load the libraries
library(chorddiag)
library(htmlwidgets)
library(dplyr)

# --- DATA LOADING AND PREPARATION ---
Chord <- read.csv("../1_Data/Data_Raw/cooccurrence_table.csv", row.names = 1)
NbArticles <- read.csv("../1_Data/Data_Raw/Upset_FieldStudy.csv")

# --- GENERATE THE INTERACTIVE CHORD DIAGRAM ---
## The chorddiag function automatically uses the order of the matrix rows/columns ##

# Transform as Matrix
co_matrix <- as.matrix(Chord)

# Set your categories
categories <- colnames(co_matrix)

# Calculate totals for group label display
article_counts <- colSums(NbArticles > 0)
group_names_with_articles <- paste0(colnames(NbArticles), "   (", article_counts, ")")

# Set you Rows and Columns Names
rownames(co_matrix) <- group_names_with_articles
colnames(co_matrix) <- group_names_with_articles

# Plot the Diagram
chord_plot <- chorddiag(
data = co_matrix,
type = "directional", # Use directional for flows, even if data is symmetric
groupNames = group_names_with_articles,
groupnamePadding = 5, # Add padding between the diagram and the labels
groupPadding = 4,      # Add space between the segments (groups)
groupnameFontsize = 10,
tooltipUnit = " co-occurrences", # Customize the unit shown in the tooltip
palette = "Set3", # Use a color palette
showTicks = FALSE)

# SAVE THE PLOT AS AN INTERACTIVE HTML FILE
saveWidget(chord_plot,
         file = "chord_diagram_interactive.html")
